    {
      "id": "ed0d80d4f7723de6182af753bfffc284ef5493f7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-09-29 05:33:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nI think the original case is valid and we still need to clean the orphans.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "cb0b28d5cc66a81ffa2dcbdea17d31e6a4af71a3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 126,
        "name": "Ned Bass",
        "email": "bass6@llnl.gov",
        "username": "nedbass"
      },
      "date": "2014-10-06 19:31:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAlex, I believe the intent of the original case was to put a bound on orphan cleanup so a buggy request from the MDS won't make OFD wipe out all its objects. Do you have an idea how to ensure proper orphan cleanup while still keeping some safeguard in place?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "664a248595b208d156a386e3e785746ff690945a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-10-20 14:28:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI think the check still makes sense, but I'd suggest to make it few times bigger. something like <max MDT file creation rate> * <max commit timeout>. 50K * 10-20?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "cd76d8d064ac90ed4d863c5cef4fcb960e1344b8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-11-10 20:29:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\nAlex, this check has been around for ages, and very rarely, if ever has it been a problem.  There was one bug LU-2251 which caught a corner case that was fixed in commit b33cba8714.  The chance of the MDS precreating so many objects on a single OST is very small, given the MDS will be allocating objects from many OSTs at once.\n\nThe current behaviour is \"more safe\" than increasing the orphan cleanup limit (at worst leaving orphan objects on the OST that LFSCK needs to clean up), compared to incorrectly deleting hundreds of thousands of objects if the orphan cleanup limit is too large.  I don't see a reason to block this patch for a potential problem that might never actually be hit.\n\nIf you think there is a problem with too many uncommitted precreates (which is only a danger with osd-zfs I think), I'd prefer to have a commit callback that tracks the number of uncommitted precreated objects, and if the uncommitted create count exceeds OST_MAX_PRECREATE / 2 it forces a commit after replying to the MDS for the precreate, rather than increasing the limit further.  That should be done in a separate patch, since I think the two problems are somewhat independent.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "ce8d31d486a7cd5926b68553191ca69bcd3086ba",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-12-11 10:39:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\nyes, I agree the exact limit is a different issue. I'd suggest to warn about the situation at least.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
